The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
		 Thursday, July 01, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Calcutta, June 30: Narayan Mondal stabbed his younger brother Pancha, 45, to death at Ghutiasharif in Canning, about 70 km from Calcutta, yesterday after the latter refused to reduce the volume of his radio. 				 																																	Additional superintendent of police B.C. Mondal said Narayan was arrested and the body sent for postmortem. 				 																																	Jhargram: Bharati, widow of Sunil Mahato who died after being kicked out of a bus on June 27 for protesting against lewd comments made at her, alleged the police were harassing her in the name of identifying the criminals. The police denied the charge.				 																																	Calcutta: Home guards will now get Rs 1 lakh as compensation, same as that offered to state police personnel, if they die in harness. The guards earlier got only Rs 25,000 as compensation. 				 																																	Calcutta: Following the success of four jail inmates in the Madhyamik examinations, the government is applying for affiliation from the West Bengal Board of Secondary Education to upgrade an informal school inside either the Alipore or the Presidency jail. 				 																																	Amlashol: A four-member BJP delegation on Wednesday visited Amlashol, where five people allegedly died of starvation, and blamed the state government for the deaths.
